        <ontology:hasEntity rdf:resource="https://dlnarratives.eu/resource/Q925943"/>
        <ontology:hasEntity rdf:resource="https://dlnarratives.eu/resource/Q48199/participant"/>
        <ontology:isPresentedBefore rdf:resource="https://dlnarratives.eu/narrative/N321_VC_18_SCA/event/ev2"/>
        <ontology:is_identified_by rdf:resource="https://dlnarratives.eu/appellation/Sami_Handicraft_-_Duodji"/>
        <ontology:partOfNarrative rdf:resource="https://dlnarratives.eu/narrative/N321_VC_18_SCA"/>
        <ontology:took_place_at rdf:resource="https://dlnarratives.eu/phenomenal_place/65.0_11.0"/>
        <ontology:hasDescription>The MOVING reference member state of this VC (Value Chain) is SKANDINAVIAN UCO. The reference MOVING Card ID of this VC is VC 18 SCA. There are two types of handicraft, the soft handicrafts and the hard ones. The first one consists of clothes, jewellery and baskets of woven birch branches and are traditionally made by women, while the hard ones are knives and cups of reindeer antlers, which are mostly manufactured by men. Traditional materials are reindeer leather, bones and antlers, natural woods, specially from birch, and silver for clothes and jewellery. Both the Sami handicraft making and souvenir purchase in Sapmi region are also touristic assets. Handicrafts can be found in stores and in Sami markets and festivals. In 1980 the Sami Duodji trademark was established for tracing authentic Sami products and , although different national organisations certify the products within each country&amp;apos;s boundaries (Norway, Sweden, Finland and Russia), the ownership rights correspond to the Sami Council.  </ontology:hasDescription>
    </NamedIndividual>
    


    <!-- https://dlnarratives.eu/narrative/N321_VC_18_SCA/event/ev10 -->


    <NamedIndividual rdf:about="https://dlnarratives.eu/narrative/N321_VC_18_SCA/event/ev10">
        <rdf:type rdf:resource="https://dlnarratives.eu/event-type/valorisation_event"/>
